<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE; 
</P>
<P>
RANCHO SECO'S SALE WEIGHED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Directors of Sacramento's citizen-owned utility district voted to slow the 
dismantling of the Rancho Seco nuclear power facility while they study offers 
by private investors to operate it. The Sacramento Municipal Utility District 
board closed the plant June 7, one day after voters ordered the utility to 
cease operating the 15-year-old facility. Since then, the five-member board has 
divided 3-2 over whether the vote mandated that Rancho Seco should be closed 
for good or whether the district has the legal right to sell it to a private 
company, which would reopen it. Opened in 1974, Rancho Seco was plagued with 
numerous shutdowns, and electricity bills of Sacramento residents almost 
doubled before the referendum June 6 in which 53% of the voters endorsed the 
closing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
